content.message: Good Morning.  Putting on my polo shirt which ironically was invented for tennis.
Who invented the shirt?
Rene "the crocodile" lacoste was the inventor.
Oh, this is the famous Izod shirt? I guess there is also Polo shirts, which are worn mostly by people not playing polo. The Hawaiians have the right idea about office attire.
For sure.  I'd rather wear the aloha shirt than a suit and tie any day.
In the UK, they call them trousers, but we in the US call them "pants."
Some cities actually have laws prohibiting "saggy pants'

I think it's a sloppy look, and probably a bit too revealing for some folks. I laughed when I saw that a D.C. judged sued a dry cleaner for millions over a lost pair of pants. I wonder whether it was for pain and suffering.
Year, $67 million to be exact.  That's crazy.  He should have been fined for such a frivolous lawsuit like that.
It's an abuse of judicial power, even if the judge hired a lawyer. I would expect a judge to throw out suits like that, since they clogs up the system.
I agree completely.  I wonder what his pants looked like.  Now if they were Aladdin's pants which were modeled after mc hammer's pants, maybe they would be worth 67 million.
I honestly expected MC Hammer's pants to be modeled after Aladdin's. It seems strange that the Romans thought pants were barbaric. I wonder why pants seem uncivilized.
Not sure, but apparently pants were originally worn by mounted armies on horseback.
I wonder how the Romans felt about socks, especially with the sandals that they wore.
I bet if got cold though they could do like the japanese and put chile peppers in the socks to keep their toes warm.
That would make for some interesting smelling feet. I didn't know that socks were originally designed to be worn with sandals. Nowadays the look is considered a goofy dad look.
Yeah, I only do that if I'm running out to get the mail or something.
The foot produces a lot of sweat, so the socks help absorb it. Maybe if a celebrity made the look popular, it would be acceptable generally.
Probably so.  Like if Billy mays work them with his blue shirts and khaki pants, that might have worked.
Who is Billy Mays?
He was the informercial guy, sold Oxy Clean for years.
I've never heard of him. Did he always wear blue shirts and khaki pants?
That was his thing.  Well, it's been nice chatting with you this morning.
Nice chatting! Bye
Hi are you a hockey fan?
Ya, you betcha. Give me a puck and a stick and you'll have a southerner trying to figure which end is up... You?
Hahahah Nice! I'm the same way.  An average pro hockey player will lose up to 8 pounds per game.
That explains why so many international hockey players are so fit! I saw in Sports Illustrated
Ha!  An ice hockey ring remains under a basketball court when switching stadium sports.  That has to be a pain in the butt changing the floor.

And I thought changing a diaper was tough... You know, hockey rinks used to only have one penalty box... But since fights would just continue in the box, teams lobbied for two boxes  to preserve teeth.
LOL ...to preserve teeth! Awesome! lol  A hockey player was traded for $1 in 1993 and he went on to win four Stanley Cups.  I have no idea what his name was.
Hockey players could use every cup they can get... In 1932, the USA Olympic hockey team lost to that hockey powerhouse, India
LOL In 1924 the first Ollympic games, Canada scored 132 goals and let in only 3 during the entire competition.  They weren't playing around.

Canadians are serious about their hockey!  Sometimes, the games get so hot, goalies spontaneously combust.  It happened once when puck hit a pack of matches in a goalie's pocket. Another reason I never smoked...
That would have been funny to see.  Canada is the only country in the world with 2 national sports hockey and lacrosse. lol

Nice. Not nice enough to make me want to be Canadian, but it is good that they have at least one thing to boast about!  Like the New England high school hockey team that beat the woman's USA Olympic team...
lol  Are you a basketball fan?  I am...my favorite shot is the granny shot.
In Texas, the Granny bow-hunting season starts in March. But Texans are proud of their Spurs, and that Tim Duncan!  He sacrificed money to stay in college for 4 years before dominating in the NBA!

Nice!  Physicists probed that shoot granny style is the absolute best technique to consistently score points from the free throw line.  That's why it's my shot.  I'm too short to get anywhere close to the hoop when the game is on.
Sounds like you still got game!  Sadly, most NBA players are broke just 5 years after they retire from the game.

Isn't that incredible they can blow through that money?  Allen Iverson will never have to worry about it after he signed that big endorsement deal with Reebok that pays him $800,000 a year until he reaches 55 and then at that time he will receive a final lump sum payment of $32 million bucks!
He's right there with Jordan...a dude so good, the Miami Heat, a team he only played against, retired Michael's Jersey number when Jordan retired. That's respect!
I never knew that.  Air Jordans were banned by the NBA.  Jordan wore them anyways because Nike was willing to pay the fine each game.  It's been fun chatting!
And now Jordan is principle owner of the Hornets!  Thanks. I have enjoyed chatting with you too!
Have a great night!
Did you ever play Tetris when you were younger?
I loved Teris on game boy!  How about you?
Sure did. I heard there is a new version available for the Playstation 4. And you can actually play it in virtual reality grabbing the blocks with your hands.
Read that as well.  Never considered Tetris to be the type of game that a VR environment would improve upon.

I wish I could afford a VR system. My son has one for his PC. I played it and was totally addicted. I was thinking of getting the one with Playstation 4 if I can ever get enough money. I also want to get Dead Red Redemption 2. I heard a reviewer say it was "jaw dropping" good.
VR scares me some, especially when designers are trying to get you addidcted

I was thinking about how people just sit in chairs hours on end staring straight ahead doing VR. Then I started thinking people used to do that with TV. After coming home from work and eating dinner they would sit in front of the TV staring straight ahead not moving for hours until they went to bed. At least with VR you are moving  your hands and with some games your whole body.
Absolutely agree and Tetris is a puzzle game that requires fast thinking, geometric skills, and other brain skills.  The jazz music will also serve to stimulate brain synapsis, so not all bad I guess

I was surprised to find out that playing it has positive effects. Like for people suffering from PTSD. Or those trying to stick to diets. I might start playing the original version again until I can get a PS4.

That is an interesting fact.  There are a few versions available on Android and Apple devices for free.  But yeah, the VR set up is going to be a super high demand product, especially for the age group that played it as a game boy game
I play GTA 5 on my PS3 now. I am really into flight simulators and that one is the best for console I think until I get a PC that can handle one. I can't believe PS3s are researching Black Holes.
I was just reading about Tetris selling 495 million copies of of its franchise.  That is enormous

I can't believe the original creator didn't get any royalties cause it went to the Soviet Union. I guess it isn't copyrighted cause there are so many free ones now. At least he started getting some royalties in 1996. I don't how with so many free versions out there.

Hopefully he will be involved in the VR version and Sony can do the right thing and get him caught up.  Did you see WII Sports is top 3 selling game?  Not sure how that is possible as that game was terrible
Actually the new one for Playstation VR was designed by Tetsuya Mizuguchi, the  Japanese designer of the game Rez, which I have never heard of. Do you play any games?
I play some mobile games, and some XBox games like Madden and NBA 2K, but not a heavy gamer by any stretch
I never did many sports games. Used to love tennis games. I don't follow sports anymore. I am into hiking in the mountains now. I have only had PSs not any XBOXs.
Healthy stuff, outdoors, always good.  I worry that VR pulls people away from that
If you play mobile games have you heard of ELOH? I play it some. I find it relaxing.  What mobile games do you recommend I try?
I like the Clash of Clans genre, Clash Royale ect.  I like the social aspect of playing with others versus solo
Sounds good. I don't get all the hype about Candy Crush. Seems boring. I'll check those out. Did you know our Department of Defense used a bunch of Playstation 3s to build a supercomputer?
Wow, interesting factoid
Are you a fan of Shaespeare?
I am a fan yeah, what about you? do you like him? his work?
I do.  I was reading up on him and discovered I don't know a lot about him as I thought he did.
There's much we dont know, he was born in the year 1564 so a lot of info is missing, he did chage our culture forever
Yes he did.  He is regarded as the greatest writer in the English language.
I have to agree with that, his plays have a mayor influence not only on Americans but on everyone, I bet Shakepeare didn't see that coming
Bet not!  He was alive at the same time as Pocahontas and they died only a year apart.  What are the odds?
I know right, makes you wonder if they ever met each other,
Be curious for sure.  Did you know he invented the names Miranda, Jessica, and Olivia?
I didn't know that but I do know he invented some of the phrases we use today
What are some of those phrases?
good riddance, wild-goose chase, brave new world. The list goes on, many popular phrases
Awesome!  Switching gears...do you like comedies?
I do like them yeah, also like mystery fictions
Which mystery fictions do you like?
Robert Ebert, one of his actually, ''Mystery and Romance of the rice cooker''
I'm not familiar with those.  I see that cat mysteries are a popular genre of fiction that involves cats as main characters solving a crime.
That doesn't sound like fun to me,  Agatha Christie is another great author
Now I've heard of her!  Her books have sold over 4 billion copies!
Yeah she is the best selling novelist of all time, her books are great,
I agree.  I've "read" her books by watching the movies, haha! Thanks for the chat!
Hi there ! Looking forward to chat with You !
Hello hows it going?  same here!  Do you like Disney?
nope :) not anymore - since they destroyed Star Wars...
lol that's funny.  The theme park is also coming out with a Star Wars land.
I'm really disappointing that huge studio like that don't understand what true devoted fans want to see in a SW movie...
That is sad.  How would you prefer to see it?
I wouldn't want to see legendary Luke Skywalker like they portrayed it...
Since,  you don't like disney,  Heres a fun fact,  Rotten tomatoes is owned by wb!
wb ? Warner Brothers ? really ? was it always like that or maybe they bought it out ?
Yes Warner Bros.  I don't actually know.  Do you think it being owned by WB has any effect on the reviews?
I think it does... I'm sure there is a pressure from WB about certain titles...
Maybe.  Also,  its nice that Netflix has 150 movies that have perfect rating on rotten tomatoes

That's quite an achievement ! I remember 2-3 years ago there was like one movie on Netflix and look what is happening now... we don't have enough time to catch up with all the shows and movies... great job NF ! :)
Right! They have some pretty amazing movie selection.
Yup ! and not like crappy movies, but actually good ones that I watched with pleasure with famous actors. This is the future of television ;)
Did you know they named it rotten tomatoes from when people use to throw tomatoes on stage.
No, I didn't know that. Really good name than  - I like it :) I just hope they are going to stay as independent as possible...
I guess that depends on Warner Bros!
dammit :) I don't trust them.... maybe we should start a company like that ? I feel like we would be good at it :) lol
Yes!  i would love to get paid to watch movies and give reviews!  Lets do it!
I was born to a job like that... :)
lol same!  Good chatting!
Good morning!  Do you watch baseball?  It can be a lucrative thing to be a fan of the game.  A man found 3 million dollars worth of baseball cards once.
I am a baseball fan. I used to collect cards but I really doubt mine are worth 3 million dollars.
After hearing about that man I wish I had collected them.  The ones he found though were from the 1900s.  They had been stashed away since the 1940s.
I could only imagine how exciting that was. My cards were from the late 1980s and 1990s, there were a lot of sets made then. I bet there were a lot less made in the 1900s.
I don't know actually.  The weird thing about baseball is that it's america's national pastime but it is super popular in Japan of all places.
I know that a few countries in Asia have really taken up baseball. A lot of former MLB players play in Korea as well.
I've heard that before.  Japan likes it so much that they are actually shocked to learn that it comes from america.
That surprises me because after World War 2 they have become a lot more open to Western culture and adopting some of our styles and customs.
It is surprising.  Speaking of surprising, did you know that the reason the managers wear uniforms is so they can go in the game if needed?
In previous years some players played a dual role as a manager as well. Now I don't think most managers would be able to last in the game.
True, some of them look a bit out of practice.  What do you think of softball?  I didn't know it was invented by the ymca.
I did not know that either. I enjoy playing softball, it is a lot more fun to play recreationally than baseball.
i like playing too.  What i learned recently was that it was originally invented as an indoor game though. I never knew that before!
I can't imagine it as an indoor game, that seems more like wiffleball to me.
It does seem odd.  You know, it's supposed to be a faster game than regular baseball and yet the longest softball game in history went for 31 innings.  That is a long game!
Any league I've played in always had rules to prevent that from happening! I couldn't imagine being involved for 31 innings, that's almost 3 baseball games.

I imagine it was pretty tiring for everyone.  Softball really doesn't get as much respect as baseball even with that super long game.  Professional players only make around 5 or 6 thousand dollars a year.
It's really hard to turn your sport into a major force in the US. With the popularity of the NFL, MLB, NBA, and NHL, they dominate the sports scene.
They definitely do at that.  It's sad to think about it though because the game has been around since 1887.
At least the YMCA created basketball and therefore one of the major sports leagues around today. Not bad for a recreational game they thought up.
True. They invented volleyball too.
Good morning. How are you doing?
Im doing great! sipping on my morning coffee. How about you?
Doing great. So what do you know about machine learning?
not a ton but I find it fascinating. There seems to be no limit to what we can do with machine learning
I know right. Ubisoft actually partnered with the british museum to have machine learning applied to reading ancient hieroglyphics.
wow, i heard about one that actually can write it's own rap lyrics
Did you know that human tests aid in the design of tests used for machine learning.
thats fascinating. I bet none of this machine learning technologies would not exist without the great invention of the telephone though!
Certainly not. I am so happy about having my phone. I dont know what I would do without it.
me too, i think everyone is pretty much addicted to their phone nowadays. We've gotten totally dependent on them
Did you know that unicef will donate a day of clean water to a child for every minute you do not use your cell phone.
thats such a nice cause. I think i can abstain from using my phone for a little bit if it means helping out children! That's easy
Heck yeah. Sign me up. Did you know that the cables to carry phone and data across the ocean is only 2.7 inches thick?
wow!! That's a thick wire if you think about it, but I wonder how the heck they got it down there any keep fish from tampering with it? must be really deep down
Im not sure. I dont even see why they need them these days with all the satellites.
they must be leftover from back in the day and theyre too much of a pain to remove at this point
Probably. Did you know that it is illegal to own a pet in boulder CO. You can however be their guardian.
thats interesting. Gives you a cooler title for sure. I wonder why that is
Probably some animal rights stuff caused it. In japan there are more pets than children under 15.
woah! I wonder if its because they're cloning pets over there. The first cloned pet was a cat aptly named Copy Cat
Lol that is funny. Well I better get off here. Have a great day.
thank you, you too!
Hello,  do you like Star Wars?
Hi! Yes I love Star Wars! How about you?
Me too, Im a big fan of Star Wars movies, which one is your favorite one?
I would have to say the very first Star Wars but they were all good I think. The Empire Strikes Back was really good too!
I liked it a lot as well but I think that the Clone Wars was better, or maybe Episode I
Good one too! It's crazy how 20th century fox thought Star Wars would be a flop! I can't imagine how much money these movies made in total!
I imagine that a lot, considereing the amount of fans the franchise has, it even was the first movie to be dubbed in navajo

Right! I thought that was awesome. I do know the first 8 films made over 8 billion....that's not including the merchandise! Star Wars holds a guiness world record for most successful merchandise franchise.
I didnt know that, thas a lot of money what I did know is that the franchise had an estimated value of 65 billion dollars!!
Wow! That is insane! Did you see Solo;A Star Wars Story? Al Pacino turned down the role of Han Solo because he didn't understand the script!
I did see that one, and thats crazy, he missed on a really big role, that would have changed his carreer for sure.
Exactly, too bad I guess lol, also they were thinking of casting Christopher Walken but don't know why he didn't get the part.
He would have been a good Han Solo, there is a hole story behind Solo, like how he was a tie fighter pilot before.
True! He would have been great in that role. I didn't know that, very interesting. I didn't know Solo; A Star Wars Story was distributed by Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures! I love Walt Disney!
Yeah, Disney bought the franchise or the rights of Star Wars, and I also love Disney, one of my favorites, The Lion King
Wow, I didn't know that. And yes I love The Lion King! it was the 1st Disney film to be dubbed into zulu for the african release, pretty cool!
I guess that answers part of the question of why Disney is so popular, did you watch Frozen?
Yes, it does! Yes, Frozen is great! And it was directed by a woman, first time for an animated film!
It is! its also interesting how the toy industry gets involved with Disney and the fimals before they even begin, a lot of money there too huh!
I know, I read that too, pretty crazy. I guess the toy industry is probably a huge part of all Disney productions!
I guess it is, and Disney is considered as one of the "Big Six" fim studios, that is pretty interesting as well.
Hello, how are you. Did you know the sun is the center of the Solar System.  It is nearly a perfect sphere of hot plasma.

I was aware of most of that. I knew it appears spherical from where we are but was not sure how uniform it actually was. I do not that it is actually white and is only perceived as being yellow which is interesting.
Really, it's actually white?  That is cool.  One second of the Sun's power is enough to power the whole planet for 500,000 years.  That is amazing.

That is impressive. Solar power is such a good idea even if we just use it as reserves. I didn't think anything could be hotter than the sun but shockingly a lightning bolt is. It's roughly 5 times hotter!
I thought the sun was the hottest of all.  As big as we think the sun is, it's only 1 billionth the size of the biggest star that has currently been discovered in our galaxy.

That is hard to wrap my head around. I can't fathom the size of that. There are many space facts that blow my mind. Like space is ever expanding but I don't understand into what. What is in the space beyond currently? Nothing?
I don't either.  That is beyond my brain power.  I guess Neptune rotates slow.  In 2011, in completed it's first full order around the sun since it's discovery in 1846.
I knew it was the farthest from the sun so it would take a while but I had no idea it took that long. That means a day is 173 years?! That's crazy!
Switching topics, did you know that JFK, Washington, and Jefferson were the 3 richest Presidents in history.
I was not aware of that. I knew the Kennedy's were wealthy. I do know that the president's guest house is larger than the white house which is interesting.
Really, that is very interesting.  President Banana was what they called the first President of Zimbabwe.
I wonder how that last name came about?
I am sure it's a funny story.  I wonder if President Trump can sing.  I saw that when the President of Indonesia was in power, he released 3 pop albums.

It's very strange that that would happen while someone was in power. Seems like something they would do before or after. I really doubt Trump can sing. The only president I can recall seeing sing ever was Obama.
Oh yeah, I remember that.  Something that I think would be useful today is that the runner up in the Presidential election automatically became the Vice President until 1805.

I was not aware of that either. That seems a little strange. They run against each other and talk about how the other is incapable and then have to work directly with that person who is then the second in line for the presidency? What a strange system.
Yes, but could be useful as well.  I am a big fan of charity and donations.  Socks are among the least often donated but are among the most needed items in homeless shelters.
Yeah I don't think I've ever seen a request for socks or know of anyone that donated them. I know that when chili peppers were introduced to Japan they were commonly put into socks to keep toes warm.
Really, I didn't know that.  The oldest pair of socks still around were designed for use with sandals.  That is pretty cool.
It is. That is not a style that is accepted now ha ha.
Well thanks for the chat.  Have a Happy New Year.
Hello.  How are you?
Hey I'm good, what do you think about humans? I know that I'm a human haha
I'm too.  Haha.  Apparently we are adapted for persistence hunting.
Yes that is interesting. Although I don't know if I got that adaptation haha. It's weird to that humans can't burp in zero gravity, I wonder if other animals can
I never heard that (human can't burp in zero gravity).  Apparently, there is a sound frequency that causes fear in humans.

That's interesting. I wonder if it's like the sound call the brown noise? Have you ever heard of that haha. Also humans are the only mammals that can't breathe and swallow at the same time, so maybe that is what is affecting our burping in zero-g
That was funny.  I was surprised to read that humans will regrow a rib within only 2-3 months after having it surgically shortened.  Have you heard that?
No I haven't. I wonder if other animals can do that? Like can we Harvest ribs from animals and have them regrow the ribs?
I don't know.  It's an interesting idea.  Apparently, human may have lost body hair as recently as 240,000 years ago.  A strange fact.
That is strange! Also, anatomically correct humans existed in Africa about 300,000 years ago, which means that anatomically correct humans had hair all over them apparently
That was also interesting.  By the way, do you like football?
Yes I think football is pretty good. I watched the Superbowl and it was good this year, what about you? What do you think
I watch football. I prefer college football to professional one though.  Apparently, the University of Iowa's locker room for visiting teams is painted pink.  I wonder why.

Yes I wonder that too, if it was to psych out the other team, it would actually make me play better I would think haha. it's crazy too, there is a high school that just build a football stadium in Texas, cost 60 million dollars
You were probably right, U of Iowa wants to psych visiting teams out.  $60 million dollars?  Are you serious?
Yep I'm serious. And it only houses 18,000 people, which seems like not a lot of people. And it's for a high-school, I don't know why they would need a football stadium of that magnitude, do you?
Do you know the name of the high school.  I live in Dallas suburb.  Americans love football.
No I don't know the name unfortunate but I do know that they are probably going to put one of those huge American flags in that Stadium. Have you heard how much those cost?
No I don't.  I'm sure it is a lot.  By the way, the highest score in a football game happened in 1916.  Georgia tech defeated Cumberland (scores 222-0).  Talking about the flag, do you know how much?
Yes so hear this, it would cost like $50,000 per flag, and each bag weighs 1100 pounds, like how is that possible? That costs as much as a car LOL
It sounds like a lot of money for a flag.  Anyway, I've got to run.  It was enjoyable chatting with you.  Take care.

Ok you have a good night, and yet it so much money. I also wonder how much Snoop jog would charge a regular High School to write their fight song LOL he did his sons for free, but I bet anyone else it would cost a lot
Good morning!  Are you a fan of Disney?
I love the franchise, its been almost 100 years of magic since the company got founded back in 1923
Walt and Roy Disney definitely knew what they were doing back in the day.
I bet they did, they changed our culture forever with the creation of Mickey Mouse and his friends.
It's funny when you think about it, isn't it?  I mean, a mouse had such a profound effect on everyone and everything.
It has, and then theres also the princess and all the other character Disney has created.
For example, Minnie Mouse.  Do you know what Minnie is short for?
No what is Minnie a short for?
Minerva.  Her name is actually Minerva Mouse.  I think Minnie suits her much better don't you?
I prefer Minnie Mouse a lot more.
Have you ever seen Big hero 6?
I have that movie was great cool fact but it was done using a 55,000 core super computer
I thought it was great too! It really surprised me that it was so good!  It's also impressive about that super computer don't you think?
It is impressive, that must be a really powerful machine, do you know who Bill Nye is?
I do. He's the science guy.  He's also a founder of the planetary society I think.
Yeah the same one, well he also appears in Flubber, he is the science consultant in that movie
That i didn't know!  I guess by having him consult they added some authenticity to the movie and to flubber itself.
It did, many people liked his show so yeah, do you like Chris Pratt?
He's okay. I've seen him in a couple of movies like guardians of the galaxy and a jurassic park one.  Do you?
I think his a great actor, I thought he was younger but he was born in the year 1979
I thought he was younger too.  I learned recently that he got discovered while waiting tables in Maui.  That's cool.  Well, I've got to go now.  It's been nice chatting with you!  Have a great day!
Hello - how are you doing this morning?
I'm doing just swell! drinking my morning cup of coffee. how about you?
I'm doing good - thanks for asking. Do you have a Netflix account?
doesnt everyone these days? haha
Haha yea. From 9pm-12am, Netflix accounts for 33% of all bandwidth in North America.
I believe it! I know thats when I get most of my Netflix watching done. and then all these kids nowadays with their "Netflix and Chilling." 9-12 is prime time for that
I bet lol. Netflix and Youtube make up half the peak internet traffic in North America.
and to think, Netflix started just because the founder racked up a big late fee on his VHS or Apollo 13!
That is funny how someone became rich over something like that. Blockbuster declined to buy Netflix for $50 million and now they are worth $2 billion.
and Blockbuster is dead. I kind of miss them though
I do miss Blockbuster myself. I used to spend a lot of time up there growing up.
i did too. every friday night I was there renting a game and a movie! Now I can just do it from home. I used to rent a lot of comedy films, one of my favorite kinds to watch
Do you like comedy films?
love em, one of my favorite genres. I could always use a good laugh. you?
Me too! 3rd Rock from the Sun won a golden globe in 1997 and beat out Seinfeld, Friends, and Frasier.
I cant believe that. Those are 3 very highly regarded shows. Im sure 3rd rock is good and all, but not as iconic
I agree. Did you know Bill Murray thinks Kung Fu Hustle is the supreme achievement of the modern age in terms of comedy?
i did hear that, I think thats an odd choice. have you ever seen that movie?
I have not seen that movie so I think it's odd as well.
definitely not in the top 250 movies of all time. 16 of which feature either Harrison Ford or Robert De Niro. Theyre each in 8
It was good talking to you!
Do you use facebook?
Yes I do.  It is such a part of my life that I still can't believe it's been around since 2004 or that I've been using it for so many years.
What do you do on it?
I guess the same things that most everyone does. That is,except for people in the german state of Schleswig-Holstein.  In that state the like button is illegal.  What do you do on it?
I only really use it for messaging people
Cool.  How do you like the blue color?
My favorite
It does seem calming.  I never questioned it but the whole reason it's blue is because Mark Zuckerburg has red-green colorblindness.
Well in any case, great choice
It must be well liked since the company is valued at $104 billion.
To the exasperation of myspace
I know what you mean there. Didn't they turn down a chance to buy facebook?
I mean I understand. I happens much like neflix and blockbuster
Yep, companies sometimes make bad decisions.  Not sure if it's bad or not but Burger king had an odd promotion on facebook where people had to unfriend others to get a free whopper.
I guess facebook rubbed them the wrong way somehow
Perhaps so.  Facebook gets most of it's revenue off of advertisements.  They may have charged Burger King too much for their ads.
Or maybe they posted something that offended burger king. I wonder how FB retaliated
I don't know.  Maybe they liked the publicity in a strange way.
I guess any publicity is good publicity?
So they say.  Facebook has the largest valuation to date for a newly listed public company so they are not hurting.
I guess you make a fair point. Anyway, thanks for chatting.
Hey there partner. Are you a soccer fan? The next World Cup is going to be in 2022 in Qatar.
I am a soccer fan and watch the world cup ever 4 years!
Nice me too! It's been around since 1930 but I feel like it's only grown in popularity since then.
Yes!  Zew Zealand was the only undefeated team in the 2010 world cup.
Well that is really awesome. In the first ever World Cup the United States got third place. Not bad for the first ever World Cup.
Not bad at all.  There was only 1 group in world cup history to end with a 4 way tie.
I'm surprised they didn't break that tie! The hungary national football team only had one defeat between 1950 and 1956 and that was the World Cup final!
That's pretty incredible.  Soccer players run an average of 7 miles per game!
No wonder they are in such incredible shape. The FIFA World Cup was not held in 1942 in 1946 due to the second world war. Very sad.
Yes.  Sad indeed.  3.2 billion people watched the 2010 FIFA world cup!
That is truly amazing. Soccer is so popular and it makes more money than football, basketball, baseball, golf, tennis, and hockey combined!
